The paper discusses the application of deep learning techniques for energy demand forecasting, which falls under the category of machine learning and artificial intelligence. Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of smart metering infrastructure, which involves the integration of hardware and software systems, making cs.SY (Systems and Control) a likely sub-category as well. The use of time series forecasting techniques also suggests cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the proposed method's performance and optimization, which falls under the category of software engineering, making cs.SE (Software Engineering) a possible sub-category.
